\title{Datacommons Client}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Work with Data Commons, a platform providing programmatic access to public statistical data from global sources. Use this skill when working with demographic data, economic indicators, health statistics, environmental data, or any public datasets available through Data Commons. Applicable for querying population statistics, GDP figures, unemployment rates, disease prevalence, geographic entity resolution, and exploring relationships between statistical entities.}

\subtree{
\title{Data Commons Client}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Provides comprehensive access to the Data Commons Python API v2 for querying statistical observations, exploring the knowledge graph, and resolving entity identifiers. Data Commons aggregates data from census bureaus, health organizations, environmental agencies, and other authoritative sources into a unified knowledge graph.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\p{Install the Data Commons Python client with Pandas support:}

\pre{\startverb
uv pip install "datacommons-client[Pandas]"
\stopverb}

\p{For basic usage without Pandas:}

\pre{\startverb
uv pip install datacommons-client
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\p{The Data Commons API consists of three main endpoints, each detailed in dedicated reference files:}

\subtree{
\title{1. Observation Endpoint - Statistical Data Queries}
\p{Query time-series statistical data for entities. See \code{\startverb references/observation.md\stopverb} for comprehensive documentation.}

\p{\strong{Primary use cases:}}

\ul{
\li{Retrieve population, economic, health, or environmental statistics}
\li{Access historical time-series data for trend analysis}
\li{Query data for hierarchies (all counties in a state, all countries in a region)}
\li{Compare statistics across multiple entities}
\li{Filter by data source for consistency}
}

\p{\strong{Common patterns:}}

\pre{\startverb
from datacommons_client import DataCommonsClient

client = DataCommonsClient()

# Get latest population data
response = client.observation.fetch(
    variable_dcids=["Count_Person"],
    entity_dcids=["geoId/06"],  # California
    date="latest"
)

# Get time series
response = client.observation.fetch(
    variable_dcids=["UnemploymentRate_Person"],
    entity_dcids=["country/USA"],
    date="all"
)

# Query by hierarchy
response = client.observation.fetch(
    variable_dcids=["MedianIncome_Household"],
    entity_expression="geoId/06<-containedInPlace+{typeOf:County}",
    date="2020"
)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Node Endpoint - Knowledge Graph Exploration}
\p{Explore entity relationships and properties within the knowledge graph. See \code{\startverb references/node.md\stopverb} for comprehensive documentation.}

\p{\strong{Primary use cases:}}

\ul{
\li{Discover available properties for entities}
\li{Navigate geographic hierarchies (parent/child relationships)}
\li{Retrieve entity names and metadata}
\li{Explore connections between entities}
\li{List all entity types in the graph}
}

\p{\strong{Common patterns:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Discover properties
labels = client.node.fetch_property_labels(
    node_dcids=["geoId/06"],
    out=True
)

# Navigate hierarchy
children = client.node.fetch_place_children(
    node_dcids=["country/USA"]
)

# Get entity names
names = client.node.fetch_entity_names(
    node_dcids=["geoId/06", "geoId/48"]
)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Resolve Endpoint - Entity Identification}
\p{Translate entity names, coordinates, or external IDs into Data Commons IDs (DCIDs). See \code{\startverb references/resolve.md\stopverb} for comprehensive documentation.}

\p{\strong{Primary use cases:}}

\ul{
\li{Convert place names to DCIDs for queries}
\li{Resolve coordinates to places}
\li{Map Wikidata IDs to Data Commons entities}
\li{Handle ambiguous entity names}
}

\p{\strong{Common patterns:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Resolve by name
response = client.resolve.fetch_dcids_by_name(
    names=["California", "Texas"],
    entity_type="State"
)

# Resolve by coordinates
dcid = client.resolve.fetch_dcid_by_coordinates(
    latitude=37.7749,
    longitude=-122.4194
)

# Resolve Wikidata IDs
response = client.resolve.fetch_dcids_by_wikidata_id(
    wikidata_ids=["Q30", "Q99"]
)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Typical Workflow}
\p{Most Data Commons queries follow this pattern:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Resolve entities} (if starting with names):}
}

\ol{
